    <section>
      <title>Why OER?</title>

      <slide>
        <title>Cost</title>

        <p>
          This is the most visible aspect of OER: it tends to be free.
        </p>

        <p>
          Cost is not unimportant: many students struggle to afford course materials.
        </p>

        <p>
          But it's not all (or we wouldn't be here)
        </p>
      </slide>

      <slide>
        <title>Flexibility</title>
        <p>
          Instructors have freedom to edit, adapt, and combine OER.
        </p>

        <p>
          <ul pause="yes">
            <li>
              <p>
                Add a chapter to a book that almost fits
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Canadianize the spelling!
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Reorganize the contents
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Fix typos
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Change a definition
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </slide>

      <slide>
        <title>Access</title>

        <p>
          Remember Fall 2020?
        </p>

        <p pause="yes">
          Did your students get their books on time?
        </p>

        <p>
          <ul pause="yes">
            <li>
              <p>
                Mine did. Early, in fact.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                OER tends to be online. Why not?
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Licensing allows students to print as needed
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                There are no access codes or crappy online viewers
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </slide>

      <slide>
        <title>Quality</title>

        <p>
          OER is free, but it's not very good, right?
        </p>

        <p pause="yes">
          (At least, according to the publisher reps)
        </p>

        <p pause="yes">
          This was true 10 years ago. It's not true any more.
        </p>

        <p pause="yes">
          Where OER still falls short, it is due to lack of people-hours to work on content.
        </p>
      </slide>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title><pretext /></title>

      <slide>
        <title><pretext /></title>

        <p>
          <url href="https://pretextbook.org" visual=""><pretext /></url> is an XML vocabulary and toolchain for authoring open textbooks.
        </p>

        <p pause="yes">
          From common source, <pretext /> can generate HTML, PDF, EPUB, Jupyter, and Braille.
        </p>

        <p pause="yes">
          <pretext /> HTML boasts features such as interactive graphics and exercises,
          live code cells, video, and a portable interface that works well on mobile devices.
        </p>

        <p pause="yes">
          You can also use it to make slides!
        </p>
      </slide>

      <slide>
        <title>Runestone</title>

        <p>
          <url href="https://runestone.academy/" visual="">Runestone Academy</url>
          is a website that provides free, interactive textbooks, mostly in computer science.
        </p>

        <p>
          The next step for <pretext /> is integration with <url href="https://pretextbook.org/examples/sample-book/noparts/html/rune.html" visual="">Runestone</url>.
        </p>

        <p>
          A <pretext /> book running on Runestone will allow students to log in,
          and complete homework, take notes, answer reading questions, <etc/>
        </p>
      </slide>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title>UTMOST</title>

      <slide>
        <title>UTMOST, v1</title>

        <p>
          <url href="https://utmost.aimath.org/" visual="">UTMOST</url>
          stands for Undergraduate Teaching in Mathematics with Open Software and Textbooks.
        </p>

        <p>
          First NSF grant funded development of SageMathCell and CoCalc,
          and the <url href="https://aimath.org/textbooks/approved-textbooks/" visual="">Open Textbook Initiative</url>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Subsequent NSF grants have funded <pretext />, and total several million dollars.
        </p>

        <subslide>
          <sidebyside width="50%" margins="40%">
            <image width="50%" source="jealous.gif"/>
          </sidebyside>
        </subslide>
      </slide>

      <slide>
        <title>UTMOST, v2</title>
        <p>
          Most recent grant used to fund <pretext /> development,
          including several AIM workshops.
        </p>

        <p pause="yes">
          One major advancement has been the development of <url href="https://aimath.org/aimnews/braille_full/" visual="">Braille</url>
          output.
        </p>

        <p pause="yes">
          Previous work used analytics (built into the book)
          to study how students used their textbooks.
        </p>

        <p pause="yes">
          Research by Vilma Mesa (University of Michigan) generated
          <url href="https://revistas.ucr.ac.cr/index.php/cifem/article/download/39908/40451/" visual="">heat maps</url>
          to show how students used their books.
        </p>
      </slide>
    </section>

    <section>
      <title>Scholarship</title>

      <slide>
        <title>My experience</title>

        <p>
          I do not hold a multi-million dollar NSF grant.
        </p>

        <subslide>
          <sidebyside width="50%" margins="40%">
            <image source="shocked.gif"/>
          </sidebyside>
        </subslide>

        <subslide>
          <p>
            But OER has been my gateway into the scholarship of teaching and learning.
          </p>

          <p>
            <ul pause="yes">
              <li>
                <p>
                  U of L Teaching Fellowship
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  The <url href="https://twitter.com/search?q=%23PreTeXtGang&amp;src=typed_query" visual="">#PreTeXtGang</url>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  FYMSiC
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  CMS
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </subslide>
      </slide>

      <slide>
        <title>Recognition and Funding</title>

        <p>
          Who funds OER in Canada? (Not NSERC)
        </p>

        <p>
          Is it recognized as scholarship?
        </p>

        <p>
          Can you even put it on your professional activities report?
        </p>

        <subslide>
          <p>
            Using OER makes us better teachers, and it reduces stress for students.
          </p>

          <p>
            OER can be better than commercial. In some cases, it already is.
            The technology is there. What we lack are (human) resources.
          </p>

          <p>
            Support for OER is support for students. We need more of it.
          </p>
        </subslide>
      </slide>
    </section>


